	abstract = {Notes that neurons in the brain communicate by short electrical pulses, the so-called action potentials or spikes. Some of the questions addressed in this work include: How can the process of spike generation be understood? How can information transmission by neurons be understood? What happens if thousands of neurons are coupled together in a seemingly random network? How does the network connectivity determine the activity patterns? How does the spike activity influence the connectivity pattern? The authors focus on phenomenological approaches so that beginners can understand the theoretical concepts before confronting the wealth of detail in biological systems. The book is in 3 parts dealing with neurons and connections, collective behavior in networks, and synaptic plasticity and its role in learning, memory, and development. Each chapter ends with a literature survey, and a comprehensive bibliography is included to introduce readers to existing research. This text is aimed at those taking courses in computational neuroscience, theoretical biology, neuronal modeling, biophysics, or neural networks. It is suitable for students of physics, mathematics, or computer science with an interest in biology, as well as biologists who are interested in mathematical modeling. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)},
